Q1. Missing data

Through the Shiny app developed in HW3, we observe abundant missing values in the MIMIC-IV ICU cohort we created. In this question, we use multiple imputation to obtain a data set without missing values.

  1. Read following tutorials on the R package miceRanger for imputation: https://github.com/farrellday/miceRanger, https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/miceRanger/vignettes/miceAlgorithm.html.

    A more thorough book treatment of the practical imputation strategies is the book Flexible Imputation of Missing Data by Stef van Buuren.

  2. Explain the jargon MCAR, MAR, and MNAR.

MCAR (Missing complete at random): the probability of being missing is the same for all cases, we say the data is MCAR. MCAR implies that causes of missing data are unrelated to the data.

MAR (Missing at random): the probability of being missing is the same only within groups defined by observed data.

MNAR (Missing not at random): Not MCAR nor MAR. The probability of being missing varies for reasons that are unknown to us.

  1. Explain in a couple of sentences how the Multiple Imputation by Chained Equations (MICE) work.

First, the algorithm will find a variable B which has strong correlation with the variable with missing data A, also another variable C. Regress A on B and obtain R^2. Randomly fill the data in the table, the R^2 will change since the fill in data are totally random. After that, use random forest to predict A by B and C. After, use A and C to predict B. Do this process repeatedly after the new R^2 is approaching the original R^2.

  1. Make imputation diagnostic plots and explain what they mean.
plotDistributions(miceObj,vars='allNumeric')

This density plot compares the original dataset and the imputed dataset. If the original numeric data plot is not matching up with the imputed value, it suggests that the data is not missing at completely random.

plotCorrelations(miceObj,vars='allNumeric')

The boxplot displays the Pearsons correlation coefficient over iteration. Its used to determine the convergence over iterations.

plotVarConvergence(miceObj,vars='allNumeric')

This plot is used to see the convergence of the imputation. Variables with divergent line spread may need more iteration. (due to the computational power, I will not do more iterations. )

plotModelError(miceObj,vars='allNumeric')

Q2. Predicting 30-day mortality

Develop at least two analytic approaches for predicting the 30-day mortality of patients admitted to ICU using demographic information (gender, age, marital status, ethnicity), first lab measurements during ICU stay, and first vital measurements during ICU stay. For example, you can use (1) logistic regression (glm() function), (2) logistic regression with lasso penalty (glmnet package), (3) random forest (randomForest package), or (4) neural network.

  1. Partition data into 80% training set and 20% test set. Stratify partitioning according the 30-day mortality status.
data = read_rds('data.rds')
train.index <- createDataPartition(data$de30, p = .8, list = FALSE)
train <- data[ train.index,]
test  <- data[-train.index,]
  1. Train the models using the training set.
y_train = as.matrix(train$de30)
x_train = as.matrix(cbind(train$gender, train$anchor_age, train$marital_status,
                          train$ethnicity, train$potassium, train$sodium,
                          train$chloride, train$bicarbonate, train$hematocrit,
                          train$wbc, train$glucose, train$magnesium, train$calcium, 
                        train$heart_rate, train$non_invasive_blood_pressure_mean, 
                        train$non_invasive_blood_pressure_systolic,
                        train$temperature_fahrenheit,train$respiratory_rate))
y_test = as.matrix(test$de30)
x_test = as.matrix(cbind(test$gender, test$anchor_age, test$marital_status,
                          test$ethnicity, test$potassium, test$sodium,
                          test$chloride, test$bicarbonate, test$hematocrit,
                          test$wbc, test$glucose, test$magnesium, test$calcium, 
                        test$heart_rate, test$non_invasive_blood_pressure_mean, 
                        test$non_invasive_blood_pressure_systolic,
                        test$temperature_fahrenheit,test$respiratory_rate))
y_train[y_train == 2] = 0
y_test[y_test == 2] = 0
